			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1802">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In &ldquo;<a href="/article/435">When They Get to the Corner</a>&rdquo; [July 2004], Sy Safransky writes, &ldquo;In a monastery, God is all you need; in a hospital room, God is health.&rdquo;</p>

<p>In the sixties, I had a lumbar fusion, which at that time kept one in the hospital for days. I made friends with an older Mexican orderly, a quiet, intelligent, funny man who came in to change my bedsheets.</p>

<p>The shock of the operation stopped my bowels from moving. Having had no bowel movement for days, I could feel death quietly, slowly entering my body. On the third day my orderly friend gave me an enema and set me up on the bed-pan, and there was a sudden and complete evacuation. The feeling of death left me. Watching my face, he said, &ldquo;Out in the world, it&rsquo;s gold and silver; in here, it&rsquo;s piss and shit.&rdquo;</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Taylor Sloan<br>Hornbrook, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1803">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I&rsquo;m not the world&rsquo;s biggest fan of Sy Safransky&rsquo;s Notebook. But his essay &ldquo;When They Get to the Corner,&rdquo; about his daughter&rsquo;s car accident and injuries, grabbed my heart. I was riveted by his beautiful story of love and vulnerability.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;ve just left my sons&rsquo; room, where I watched them sleep, safe for the moment as we hurtle into an unknown future.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Dori Schack<br>Santa Cruz, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="1804">
								<p><a href="/contributors/sy-safransky"><strong>Sy Safransky</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>Following the publication of my essay, I received numerous letters expressing concern about my daughter&rsquo;s health. Happily, Mara is completely recovered: able to walk, to run, and, when she reflects on her good fortune, to leap for joy.</p>
	</div>


					</div>

